Introduction¶

Today, one of the biggest problems the world is facing is the state of the environment.Climate Change and the warming of the earth will impact everyone and many scientists believe that countries need to act immediately. Yet, when discussing this issue many wonder who is causing the most impact. Is it the rich, developed countries or poorer, undeveloped countries?

Therefore, the purpose of this project is to use data analytics to help understand the relatioship between wealth and environental impact. Simultaneously,we will also analyze wealth trends and learn how wealth is dispersered throughought the world. To perform this study, we will be using the following indicators obtained from Gapminder database: CO2 emmisions per person(tonnes/person), GNI per captia (Atlas method), Energy production per person ( tonnes of oil equivalent/person), and Percent Agricultural Land. Gapminder provides data over many years for each country.

Aligning Years¶

By observing the data it is clear that the years for the indicators to not match. Therefore, it would be best to align them before merging. By observig the data, we find that the latest year that the data is collected is 1962, and the earliest year data collection stops is 2010. Therefore, we shall cap all indicators to ths time frame.

In [9]:
# take alll data from 1962 on
farm=farm[farm["Year"]>="1962"]
energy=energy[energy["Year"]>="1962"]
carbon=carbon[carbon["Year"]>="1962"]
In [14]:
# Find earliest year data collection stops
min(max(carbon["Year"]),max(gni["Year"]),max(energy["Year"]), max(farm["Year"]))
Out[14]:
'2010'
In [10]:
# takes data before 2010. 
carbon=carbon[carbon["Year"]<="2010"]
farm=farm[farm["Year"]<="2010"]
energy=energy[energy["Year"]<="2010"]
gni=gni[gni["Year"]<="2010"]
In [11]:
# reset index
carbon=carbon.reset_index(drop=True)

gni=gni.reset_index(drop=True)
gni["index"]=gni.index
farm["index"]= farm.index
energy["index"]= energy.index
gni["carbon"]=gni.index

Interpolation¶

The previous strategy greatly reduced the number of missing vaues. Now, there are no missing values for Country, Year, CO2 emissions and Energyt Production. Also, there are insignificant amount of missing values for GNI and Agricultural Land. These few missing values can be interpolated by taking the average value of the indicator for the respective country.

In [17]:
table_3=table_2.copy()
In [18]:
# interpolate for GNI
table_3['GNI'] = table_3.groupby('Country').GNI.transform(lambda x: x.fillna(x.mean()))
In [19]:
# interpolate for Agricultural Land
table_3['perct_Farm_Land'] = table_3.groupby('Country').perct_Farm_Land.transform(lambda x: x.fillna(x.mean()))

Feature Engineering¶

To analyze wealth trends and its relationship with the indcators, it would be benificial classify each country based on its wealth. The World Bank has a wealth classification system that utilizes GNI/capita.

The World Bank defines high-income nations as having a GNI of at least 12,276 dollars per capita, defines lower middle income countries as having a GNI that ranges from 1,006 to 3,975 dollars per capita and upper middle income countries as having a GNI ranging from 3,976 to 12,275 dollars per capita. Any country below 1,006 dollars per capita is low-income.

In [21]:
# implement Wealth Classification
classifications=[]
for i in table_3["GNI"]: 
    if i >12275: 
        x= "high_income"
    elif 3975 <i <12276: 
        x="upper_middle_income"
    elif 3976>i>1005: 
        x="lower_middle_income"
    elif i<1006: 
        x="low_income"
    classifications.append(x)
In [22]:
# Add to Dataframe
table_3["Income_classification"]= classifications

Over this ten year period, the number of low income countries has decreased rapidly. The number of lower middle income countries also decreased. However, the number of high income and upper middle income countries has increased. This graph depicts an interesting phenomenon. In the beginning of the period, there were more poorer countries than wealther countries. Yet, by the end of the period, the distribution had changed completely. This indicates that the world is getting wealthier.

# Function Creates a series of scatter subplots which compare the relationhip between two variables.
# It also calculates the correlation coefficient. 
        
def plot(x1,x2,x3,x4,x5,x6,x7,x8,x9,x10,x11,y1,y2,y3,y4,y5,y6,y7,y8,y9,y10,y11,name,labelx,labely,x,y): 
    plt.figure(figsize=(23,23))
    plt.subplot(3, 4, 1)

    plt.scatter(x1, y1)
    plt.title("1999:"+" "+name)
    plt.xlabel(labelx)
    plt.ylabel(labely)
    plt.text(x=x,y=y,s="r"+":"+" "+str(round(np.corrcoef(x1,y1)[0][1],3)), fontsize=15)


    plt.subplot(3, 4, 2)
    plt.scatter(x2, y2)
    plt.title("2000:"+" "+name)

Carbon Emissions¶

Throughout the timeframe, it is clear that CO2 and GNI/person are strongly correlated as the r values see to range from .577 to .701. Also, the scatter plots depict the presence of outliers. We notice that large values of CO2 are only present with large GNIs. This suggests that the the CO2 emmisions may be concentrated to a few wealthy countries.

This table, which depicts the average vaue of the indicators based on income classification confirms the notion that CO2 emissions, GNI and Energy production are concentrated in wealth countries. The large differences between high income and low income observed could be attributed to the previously observed phenomena of concentration and outliers.

Conclusions¶

From this study, we observed a trend which suggests that the world is becoming wealthier. Also, it seems like the majority of the world's wealth is concentrated in a few countries. From the environmental indicators observed, we see an overall increase in CO2 emmissions, a decrease in Farmland, and a parabolic trend for energy production. When observing the scatter plots and r values between the environmental idicators, we noticed a strong positive correlation between GNI and CO2 emissions, a positive correlation between GNI and energy production, and a weak negative correlation between farmland and GNI. Also, by observing the scatter plots we noticed the presence of outliers for CO2 emissions and Energy production, which could suggest the that a majority of CO2 emssions and Energy Production is with the Wealthy Countries. This phenomea was also observed by analyzing the average values based on the Wealth Classification. Going forward, it would be benificial to conduct statistical tests like p-value to determine whether the results are statistically significant.
